[[File:Ideal framställning av eleusinska jämte atenska gudomligheter och eleusinska präster, Nordisk familjebok.png|thumb|300px|Drawing of Eleusinian figures around the neck of the '''Queen of Vases''', pictured center]] [[File:'Regina Vasorum', 4th century BCE, southern Italy, The Hermitage.JPG|thumb|Photo of the '''Regina Vasorum'''; the [[hydria]] stand 65.5cm high<ref name=hermitage>http://www.hermitagemuseum.org/wps/portal/hermitage/digital-collection/25.+Archaeological+Artifacts/289706/?lng=en</ref>]]
The '''''Regina Vasorum''''' or '''Queen of Vases''' is a 4th-century BC [[hydria]] from [[Cumae]] depicting [[Eleusinian Mysteries|Eleusinian]] divinities with [[Gilding|gilded]] flesh in [[polychrome]] [[relief]]. It is held in the collections of the [[Hermitage Museum]], [[St. Petersburg]]. In addition to its aesthetic qualities, it is valued as an [[iconography|iconographical]] source for [[Religion in ancient Greece|ancient Greek religion]].
The ''Regina Vasorum'' is a "spectacular" and unusually large example of technical experimentation among [[Pottery of Ancient Greece|Greek potters]] after the [[Red-figure pottery|red-figure style]] had run its course.<ref>Harvey Alan Shapiro, Carlos A. Picón, Gerry D. Scott, "Introduction to South Italian Vases," in ''Greek Vases'' (San Antonio Museum of Art, 1995), p. 252 [https://books.google.com/books?id=za3_C_J3jQgC&pg=PA252&dq=%22regina+vasorum%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=4#v=onepage&q=%22regina%20vasorum%22&f=false online.]</ref> The figures were made separately, painted, and gilded, then attached to the vase with [[slip (ceramics)|slip]],<ref name=hermitage/> possibly by [[Sprigging (pottery)|sprigging]].
==See also== * [[South Italian Ancient Greek pottery]]
==Sources== * Elena Ananitch, ''Lucanian Vases'' («L'Erma» di Bretschneider, 2005), p.&nbsp;7 [https://books.google.com/books?id=EYkZIDjue9sC&pg=PA7&dq=%22queen+of+vases%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=0&cd=11#v=onepage&q=%22queen%20of%20vases%22&f=false online.] * Kevin Clinton, ''Greek Sanctuaries'' p.&nbsp;92 [https://books.google.com/books?id=7yUjHQjGHyMC&pg=PA92&dq=%22regina+vasorum%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=5#v=onepage&q=%22regina%20vasorum%22&f=false online.] * Beth Cohen, ''The Colors of Clay: Special Techniques in Athenian Vases'' (J. Paul Getty Museum, 2006), p.&nbsp;115. * Erika Simon, ''Festivals of Attica: An Archaeological Commentary'' (University of Wisconsin Press, 1983), ''passim''.
