The '''Yamaha Music Foundation''' is an organization established in 1966 by the authority of the [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology|Japanese Ministry of Education]] for the purpose of promoting [[music education]] and music popularization. It continued a program of music classes begun by [[Yamaha Corporation]] in 1954.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of the Yamaha Music Foundation|url=http://www.yamaha-mf.or.jp/english/about/history.html|publisher=Yamaha Music Foundation|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> Its unique, systematic teaching method and [[Teacher education|teacher training]] programs are highly valued in [[Japan]] and other countries.<ref>{{Citation | last = | first = | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | title =Music School Opened In Lexington, MA (Yamaha) | newspaper =Music Trades| pages = | year = | date =June 1, 2006 | url =http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-147218120.html| archiveurl = | archivedate = | accessdate =November 12, 2012 }}</ref>

The ''Yamaha Grade Examination System'' has been developed to enable students and teachers to ensure their own progress and thereby obtain [[self-confidence]] in their own music studies.  The Yamaha Grade Examination System consists of nine grades, Grade 9 to Grade 1. The [[Test (assessment)|examination]] evaluates the performing ability of the music lovers in general; the performing ability and the musical knowledge and techniques required for the instructors of the fundamentals stage; and also the performing competence of the [[Music artist (occupation)|professional musicians]].

The foundation is known for its organizing of the [[World Popular Song Festival]]<ref>{{Citation | last =Egluchi | first =Hideo | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | title =Tokyo World Fest Draws 40 Songs; 6 Entered By Japan | newspaper =Billboard Magazine| pages =64 | year = | date =November 10, 1973 | url = | archiveurl = | archivedate = | accessdate =November 12, 2012 }}</ref> which it organized from 1970 until 1989.

